<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ910619-0176</DOCNO><DOCID>910619-0176.</DOCID><HL>   Mutual Benefit   Is Exploring Ways   To Raise Capital   ----   By Susan Pulliam   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal</HL><DATE>06/19/91</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE C11</SO><MS>FINANCIAL (FIN)</MS><IN>LIFE INSURANCE (INL)INSURANCE (INS)TENDER OFFERS, MERGERS, ACQUISITIONS (TNM)</IN><NS>ACQUISITIONS andamp; MERGERS, TAKEOVERS, BOARD BATTLES (TNM)</NS><RE>NORTH AMERICA (NME)UNITED STATES (US)</RE><LP>   Mutual Benefit Life Insurance Co., which has been hurt bysouring real estate investments, is trying to raise at least$300 million in new capital and is eager to strike a quickdeal, according to a confidential offering memo circulated topotential investors.   The Newark, N.J., insurer, which has assets of $13billion, is also taking steps to calm agents andpolicyholders after the company announced a restructuringplan in May and its credit ratings were sharply downgraded.Among other things, the company said it will continue somesales of individual life insurance policies that itpreviously said it would suspend.</LP><TEXT>   In the offering memo, Mutual Benefit said it isconsidering a number of possible restructuring plans inaddition to those that it announced last month. The companyis willing to merge with another company or enter a jointventure, management agreements or reinsurance transactions,it said. Moreover, the document stresses that Mutual Benefitis flexible and wants to act quickly. The company is beingadvised by Smith Barney, Harris Upham andamp; Co., a unit ofPrimerica Corp.   Last month, Mutual Benefit announced plans to restructureits business after merger talks with Metropolitan LifeInsurance Co. fell through. As part of the plan, the companysaid it would sell a stake to an investor in its groupinsurance business and sharply cut back its individual lifeinsurance business.   As part of the restructuring, Mutual Benefit will reduceits headquarters staff of 1,400 by 20% to 40%, StephenCarlotti, chief operating officer, disclosed in an interviewyesterday.   Mutual Benefit revised its plans to discontinue sales ofmost of its individual insurance products in part because ofpressure from the company's general agents, whose sales wouldhave suffered under the original plan, Mr. Carlotti said.</TEXT></DOC>